# Never Bypass TypeScript Type Safety

## Rule

FORBIDDEN type safety bypasses:
- Explicit `any` type annotations
- `@ts-expect-error` directives
- `@ts-ignore` directives
- `// @ts-nocheck` directives

ALWAYS use proper TypeScript types instead.

## Context

The `any` type and TypeScript error suppression directives disable type checking and defeat the purpose of using TypeScript. They hide real type issues that can cause runtime errors.

Type errors should be resolved properly by defining correct interfaces, not suppressed.

## No Explicit `any` Type

### Why any is dangerous

Using `any` disables type checking, prevents IDE autocompletion, and can mask bugs. It should be avoided in favor of proper typing or the safer `unknown` type.

### Safe alternatives to any

1. `unknown` - For truly unknown data (requires type guards)
2. Union types - `string | number | boolean` for known possibilities
3. Generic types - `<T>` for reusable functions/components
4. Interface extensions - Extend existing types with missing properties
5. Type assertions - `as SpecificType` with proper interfaces

### Examples

Incorrect:
```typescript
function handleData(data: any) {
  return data.someProperty;
}

const subscription: any = stripeSubscription;
const result: any[] = await apiCall();

function process(data: any): any {
  // ...
}
```

Correct:
```typescript
interface DataType {
  someProperty: string;
}
function handleData(data: DataType) {
  return data.someProperty;
}

interface StripeSubscriptionWithPeriod extends Stripe.Subscription {
  current_period_start: number;
  current_period_end: number;
}
const subscription = stripeSubscription as StripeSubscriptionWithPeriod;

interface ApiResult {
  id: string;
  name: string;
}
const result: ApiResult[] = await apiCall();

function process<T>(data: T): T {
  // ...
}
// OR
function process(data: unknown): ProcessedData {
  // ...
}
```

### Type extension pattern

For external libraries missing type definitions:

Incorrect:
```typescript
const stripeObject: any = subscription;
```

Correct:
```typescript
interface ExtendedStripeSubscription extends Stripe.Subscription {
  current_period_start: number;
  current_period_end: number;
}

const stripeObject = subscription as ExtendedStripeSubscription;
```

## No @ts-expect-error or @ts-ignore

### Why error suppression is dangerous

TypeScript errors indicate type mismatches that can cause runtime issues. Suppressing them masks problems instead of fixing them.

### Examples

Incorrect:
```typescript
// @ts-expect-error - DialogContent has type definition issues
<DialogContent className="max-w-lg">
  <div>Content</div>
</DialogContent>

// @ts-ignore
const result = someFunction(invalidArgument);

// @ts-expect-error
const data = response.data;
```

Correct:
```typescript
// Option 1: Component composition
<DialogContent>
  <div className="max-w-lg">
    <div>Content</div>
  </div>
</DialogContent>

// Option 2: Wrapper component with proper types
const StyledDialogContent = ({ children, ...props }) => (
  <DialogContent {...props}>
    {children}
  </DialogContent>
);

// Option 3: Type assertion with proper interface
<DialogContent {...({className: "max-w-lg"} as ComponentProps<typeof DialogContent>)}>
  <div>Content</div>
</DialogContent>

// Fix argument type
const result = someFunction(validArgument);

// Proper type assertion
const data = response.data as ExpectedType;
```

### Component wrappers for type safety

For shadcn/ui or third-party components with type issues:

Incorrect:
```typescript
// @ts-expect-error - DialogContent has type issues
<DialogContent className="custom-class">
```

Correct:
```typescript
// Option 1: Component composition
<DialogContent>
  <div className="custom-class">
    {/* content */}
  </div>
</DialogContent>

// Option 2: Typed wrapper
interface StyledDialogProps {
  className?: string;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

const StyledDialog: React.FC<StyledDialogProps> = ({ className, children }) => (
  <DialogContent>
    <div className={className}>
      {children}
    </div>
  </DialogContent>
);
```

### Type assertions with interfaces

Incorrect:
```typescript
// @ts-ignore - third party library types missing
library.someMethod(data);
```

Correct:
```typescript
interface LibraryMethod {
  someMethod: (data: DataType) => ReturnType;
}
(library as LibraryMethod).someMethod(data);
```

### Using unknown for truly unknown data

Incorrect:
```typescript
// @ts-expect-error
function processData(data: any) {
  return data.someProperty;
}
```

Correct:
```typescript
function processData(data: unknown) {
  if (typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && 'someProperty' in data) {
    return (data as { someProperty: unknown }).someProperty;
  }
  throw new Error('Invalid data format');
}
```

## Proper Solutions Summary

### For component type issues
1. Use component composition (wrapper divs)
2. Create properly typed wrapper components
3. Use type assertions with defined interfaces
4. Use ComponentProps utility type

### For function parameters
1. Define specific interfaces for known structures
2. Use `unknown` with type guards for unknown data
3. Use generic types for reusable code
4. Extend existing types when needed

### For external library gaps
1. Create interface extensions
2. Define missing type declarations
3. Use type assertions with proper interfaces
4. Never use `any` as a shortcut

## Exceptions

There are NO acceptable exceptions for using `any` or TypeScript error suppression in this codebase.

If you encounter type errors:
1. Understand the root cause of the type mismatch
2. Fix the types by defining proper interfaces
3. Refactor the code if needed to work with the type system
4. Create wrapper components if working around third-party limitations

## Checklist for the Assistant

- [ ] Never suggest `any` type annotations
- [ ] Never suggest `@ts-expect-error` in any context
- [ ] Never suggest `@ts-ignore` in any context
- [ ] Always define proper interfaces for object structures
- [ ] Use `unknown` instead of `any` for truly unknown data
- [ ] Create type extensions for external libraries missing properties
- [ ] Use generic types for reusable functions and components
- [ ] Prefer union types over `any` for known possibilities
- [ ] Create wrapper components when needed for type safety
- [ ] Use proper type assertions with defined interfaces

## Remember

TypeScript errors exist to prevent runtime issues. Suppressing them or using `any` defeats the purpose of using TypeScript and can introduce bugs. Always fix the root cause with proper types.
